        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, the smell of damp earth in his mother\u2019s Daly City floral shop. His father, smelling of oil and industry, was on the floor fixing the rattling floral cooler. When he finished, his mother didn\u2019t offer a spreadsheet of savings, but a single, perfect white calla lily. The silent exchange taught him that practicality and beauty weren\u2019t opposites; one was the sturdy scaffolding that allowed the other to bloom. It became the core principle of his life.\n\n2.\nAt fourteen, he obsessively rearranged his bedroom. It wasn\u2019t just cleaning; he curated his worn paperbacks, band posters, and a single lucky cat into a cohesive scene. His dad saw chaos in the constant change, but his mom, peering in, saw composition. \u201cIt tells a story,\u201d she\u2019d said softly. That whisper of approval was the first time he felt his unique way of seeing the world wasn't a flaw to be corrected, but a language he inherently spoke.\n\n3.\nHe was 23, armed with a tiny budget for the forgotten secondary holiday window in Union Square. He worked past midnight, wiring salvaged market lights around bare branches he\u2019d painted silver. When he stepped back onto the cold sidewalk, he saw his display, born of scarcity, had more soul than the main window\u2019s expensive glare. It was the moment he realized his vision, not his budget, was his true professional capital, a validation that felt like sunlight.\n\n4.\nLast winter, on the 5-Fulton, rain slicked the windows, blurring the city into watercolor. The bus stopped, framing a vibrant mural on a Divisadero wall. The neon orange of a woman\u2019s raincoat against the mural's deep teal became the entire color story for the next season's launch. In that quiet moment, his daily commute wasn\u2019t a chore but his most vital creative tool\u2014a private, moving collaboration with the city he called home.\n\n5.\nA few months ago, after a sterile corporate meeting about maximizing profit-per-square-foot, he walked through Hayes Valley. He watched a shop owner lovingly adjusting a single ceramic vase in her window, an act of pure intention. The quiet pride on her face struck him like lightning. It wasn\u2019t about scale; it was about soul. That evening, he filled a new sketchbook not with designs for his employer, but with layouts for his own store."
